  <body class="portfolio-details-page">
    <Navbar />

    <main class="main">
      <!-- Page Title -->
      <div class="page-title accent-background">
        <div class="container">
          <h1>Bookstop</h1>
          <nav class="breadcrumbs">
            <ol>
              <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
              <li><a href="/Projects">Projects</a></li>
              <li><a href="/LangChain">LangChain Projects</a></li>
              <li class="current">Bookstop</li>
            </ol>
          </nav>
        </div>
      </div><!-- End Page Title -->

      <!-- Portfolio Details Section -->
      <section id="portfolio-details" class="portfolio-details section">
        <div class="container" data-aos="fade-up">
          <div class="portfolio-details-slider swiper init-swiper">
            <script type="application/json" class="swiper-config">
              {
                "loop": true,
                "speed": 600,
                "autoplay": {
                  "delay": 5000
                },
                "slidesPerView": "auto",
                "navigation": {
                  "nextEl": ".swiper-button-next",
                  "prevEl": ".swiper-button-prev"
                },
                "pagination": {
                  "el": ".swiper-pagination",
                  "type": "bullets",
                  "clickable": true
                }
              }
            </script>
            <div class="swiper-wrapper align-items-center">
              <div class="swiper-slide">
                <img
                  src="/assets/img/langchain/bookstop/booklangbg.png"
                  alt=""
                />
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="swiper-button-prev"></div>
            <div class="swiper-button-next"></div>
            <div class="swiper-pagination"></div>
          </div>

          <div class="row justify-content-between gy-4 mt-4">
            <div class="col-lg-8" data-aos="fade-up">
              <div class="portfolio-description">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                <p>
                  The Cloudstaff Library Assistant is an AI-powered chatbot
                  application designed to help Cloudstaff employees interact
                  with the company’s library resources. Built using Python and
                  LangChain, the assistant leverages natural language
                  understanding to provide real-time responses related to books
                  and library services. The application enhances access to book
                  recommendations, availability checks, and general library
                  discussions.
                </p>
                <div class="row align-items-center">
                  <div class="col-md-6 d-flex justify-content-center">
                    <img
                      src="/assets/img/langchain/bookstop/bookstoplang.png"
                      class="img-fluid zoomable-image"
                      style="max-width: 80%; height: auto; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; cursor: pointer;"
                      data-bs-toggle="modal"
                      data-bs-target="#imageModal"
                      onclick="setModalImage(this.src, this.alt)"
                    />
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Email Authentication UI</h3>
                    <p>
                      Includes fields to enter a Cloudstaff email and password.
                      A "Verify Email" button is added for authenticating users
                      before accessing the chatbot. The Firebase authentication
                      restricts access to users with @cloudstaff.com emails.
                    </p>
                    <h3>Book Availability Check</h3>
                    <p>
                      Users can instantly check if a specific book is available
                      in the Cloudstaff library's collection. The chatbot uses
                      vector-based search to match book titles, even if the
                      input has slight variations or typos (e.g., "Atomic
                      Habitz" → "Atomic Habits"). It pulls from a structured
                      library database or embedded documents for precise
                      responses.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <br>
                <br>
                <div class="row align-items-center">
                  <div
                    class="col-md-6 order-md-2 d-flex justify-content-center"
                  >
                    <img
                      src="/assets/img/langchain/bookstop/bookstoplang2.png"
                      class="img-fluid zoomable-image"
                      style="max-width: 80%; height: auto; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; cursor: pointer;"
                      data-bs-toggle="modal"
                      data-bs-target="#imageModal"
                      onclick="setModalImage(this.src, this.alt)"
                    />
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-md-6 order-md-1">
                    <h3>Book Discussions</h3>
                    <p>
                      The assistant can engage in book-related conversations
                      such as: Comparing two books Discussing an author's
                      writing style Talking about literary themes or book
                      endings This feature enhances user engagement and
                      simulates a more human-like interaction—ideal for book
                      lovers and discussion-oriented users.
                    </p>
                    <h3>Intelligent Query Handling</h3>
                    <p>
                      The chatbot uses an LLM-powered classifier (via LangChain)
                      to determine whether a user query is: Book-related (e.g.,
                      recommendations, availability, discussions)
                      General-purpose (e.g., “What’s the weather?” or “Tell me a
                      joke”) Non-library queries can be politely declined or
                      redirected, depending on the intended app behavior,
                      helping the assistant stay focused on its core use case.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <br>
                <br>
                <div class="row align-items-center">
                  <div class="col-md-6 d-flex justify-content-center">
                    <img
                      src="/assets/img/langchain/bookstop/bookstoplang1.png"
                      class="img-fluid zoomable-image"
                      style="max-width: 80%; height: auto; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; cursor: pointer;"
                      data-bs-toggle="modal"
                      data-bs-target="#imageModal"
                      onclick="setModalImage(this.src, this.alt)"
                    />
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h3>Vector Database for Efficient Retrieval</h3>
                    <p>
                      The application integrates a vector database (e.g.,
                      Chroma, FAISS, or Weaviate) to store semantic embeddings
                      of book descriptions and metadata. This enables: Semantic
                      search: Matching queries with similar meaning, not just
                      exact keywords Scalable performance: Fast and accurate
                      retrieval even with a growing book collection This
                      architecture improves the relevance and speed of query
                      results dramatically.
                    </p>
                    <h3>User-Friendly Interface with Gradio</h3>
                    <p>
                      Built using Gradio, the app features a responsive and
                      accessible UI: Easy-to-use login section with
                      email/password Interactive chatbot window Suggested quick
                      prompts to help users get started Visually appealing
                      layout with branding aligned to Cloudstaff This makes the
                      app accessible to non-technical users while providing a
                      sleek, professional experience.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-3" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="100">
              <div class="portfolio-info sticky">
                <h3>Project Information</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Developer</strong> LangChain Team</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Technology</strong> LangChain<br />OpenAI & Google
                    Generative AI<br />ChromaDB<br />Gradio<br />Pandas & NumPy
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
      <!-- /Portfolio Details Section -->
    </main>

    <Footer />
    <Modal />

    <!-- Scroll Top -->
    <a
      href="#"
      id="scroll-top"
      class="scroll-top d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center"
      ><i class="bi bi-arrow-up-short"></i></a
    >

